            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Scott Miller\u2019s story is a classic San Francisco transplant tale, albeit one with a Gen X twist. Raised in a quiet Portland suburb by a pragmatic accountant father and a literature-loving teacher mother, Scott grew up revering the printed word. Fueled by visions of Woodward and Bernstein, he pursued a journalism degree from the University of Oregon, arriving in San Francisco in the late \u201890s. He landed a coveted job at an alt-weekly, spending his twenties and thirties chronicling the city\u2019s vibrant, chaotic soul one byline at a time. He loved the grit, the deadlines, and the feeling that he was documenting history.\n\nThe digital tsunami of the late 2000s washed away his publication and the career he\u2019d envisioned. Facing dwindling prospects and with a mortgage to pay, Scott made the pragmatic pivot that defined his second act. He traded his reporter's notebook for corporate style guides, reframing his journalistic skills for the burgeoning tech industry. The transition felt like a betrayal at first, but survival\u2014and a steady paycheck\u2014won out.\n\nNow a Senior Content Strategist, Scott earns a comfortable living shaping the narrative for a large information-services company. The irony is not lost on him. His daily 2.5-mile bicycle commute from his lovingly maintained NoPa apartment to his sleek SoMa office is a cherished ritual, a moment of analog peace in a digital world. Divorced amicably a decade ago, his life is now a well-worn groove of work, weekend rides in the Marin Headlands, and quiet evenings with his cat, Kerouac. He maintains a tight circle of friends\u2014a mix of grizzled ex-journalists and younger tech colleagues\u2014who meet for craft beers to debate city politics.\n\nAt 51, Scott\u2019s aspirations have shifted from breaking news to finding balance. He dreams of finally writing a non-fiction book about the very media collapse he survived, a final piece of reportage to make sense of his journey from storyteller to strategist. He remains deeply connected to San Francisco, a city that both broke his heart and rebuilt his career, finding contentment in the foggy evenings and the steep hills he now calls home."
